>Gerard</i>. <i>Gerard</i> in Middle English was indistinguishable from <i>Gerald</i>, of which <i>Gelle</i> was a syncopated form.","English: occasionally, a variant of   Gill  , from a pet form of the personal name <i>Jelion</i> or <i>Gillian</i>. These are Middle English versions of <i>Julian</i>, found mainly as a female name, occasionally as a male name.","Manx: variant of   Gill  , a shortened form of Gaelic <b>Mac Gille</b>, meaning ‘son of the lad (i.e. servant)’."],"variants":[{"name":"Gill","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Avtar, Amritpal, Darshan, Hardip, Nirmal, Sohan, Ajit, Balwinder, Charan, Jasvir, Kewal, Navdeep.","English and Scottish: in northern England and Scotland sometimes from Middle English <i>Gille</i>, Old Norse <i>Gilli</i>, which is of Irish (Gaelic) origin (see below), and pronounced with a hard <i>g</i>. As a personal name it is not found after <i>c.</i> 1200.","English and Scottish: topographic name from Middle English <i>gille</i> ‘deep glen, ravine’ (Old Norse (Norwegian) <i>gil</i>), pronounced with a hard <i>g</i>. The term is found mainly in northwestern England, where Norwegian Vikings settled."]}]},{"name":"Ralph","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From a Norman French name, <i>Raulf</i>, a contracted form of the Germanic personal name <i>Radulf</i>, derived from <i>rād</i> ‘counsel’ + <i>wulf</i> ‘wolf’. The spelling with <i>-ph</i> is due to classical influence in the 18th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Ralf","meanings":["From a Norman French name, <i>Raulf</i>, a contracted form of the Germanic personal name <i>Radulf</i>, derived from <i>rād</i> ‘counsel’ + <i>wulf</i> ‘wolf’. The spelling with <i>-ph</i> is due to classical influence in the 18th century."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs. Ralph Gell was born about 1380, in Wirksworth, Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom. She married Ralph GYLES II about 1400, in Wirksworth, Der